options(scipen = 999) #turn off scientific notation like 1e+06
data('midwest', package = 'ggplot2') # load the data

Initialize ggplot with rows and columns to use for x and y:

ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal))

Now we add a scatterplot:

ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) + 
  geom_point()

And a fit line:

ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se = F) #se = F remove the confidence interval for the fit line
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Lets change the y limit:

METHOD A:

delete points outside the range

g <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm')

g + xlim(c(0, 0.1)) + ylim(c(0, 1000000))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 5 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

METHOD B: zoom-in without deleting values

g1 <- g + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000))

plot(g1)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Change title and axis labels

g1 + labs(title = 'Area Vs Population', subtitle = 'From midwest dataset', y = 'Population', x = 'Area', caption = 'Midwest Demographics')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Or, equivalently:

g1 + ggtitle('Area vs Population', subtitle = 'From midwest dataset') +
  xlab('Area') + ylab('Population')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Change color and size of points

ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) +
  geom_point(col = 'steelblue', size = 3) +        #set static color and size for points
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', col = 'firebrick') +  #change color of the line
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000)) +
  labs(title = 'Area Vs Population', subtitle = 'From midwest dataset', y = 'Population', x = 'Area', caption = 'Midwest Demographics')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Change color of the points based on another column

gg <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) +
  geom_point(aes(col = state), size = 3) +          #set color to vary based on state categories
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', col = 'firebrick', size = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000)) +
  labs(title = 'Area Vs Population', subtitle = 'From midwest dataset', y = 'Population', x = 'Area', caption = 'Midwest Demographics')

gg
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Remove legend

gg + theme(legend.position = 'None') #remove legend
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Change colours

gg + scale_colour_brewer(palette = 'Set1')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

change axes text and labels

Base plot:

gg <- ggplot(midwest, aes(x = area, y = poptotal)) +
  geom_point(aes(col = state), size = 3) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', col = 'firebrick', size = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 0.1), ylim = c(0, 1000000)) +
  labs(title = 'Area Vs Population', subtitle = 'From midwest dataset', y = 'Population', x = 'Area', caption = 'Midwest Demographics')

breaks: We used scale_x_continuous because x is continuous, but we could also have used scale_x_date

gg + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 0.1, by = 0.01))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Labels

gg + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 0.1, by = 0.01), labels = letters[1:11])
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Customized text for axis labels

METHOD 1:

using sprintf(), we are going to use it for x.

METHOD 2:

using a custom user defined function, we are going to use it for y:

gg + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 0.1, 0.01), labels = sprintf("%1.2f%%", seq(0, 0.1, 0.01))) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 1000000, 200000), labels = function(x){paste0(x/1000, 'K')})
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Customize the entire theme with pre-built themes

If we change it BEFORE plotting:

theme_set(theme_classic())
plot(gg)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

If we change it AFTER plotting:

gg + theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

gg + theme_classic()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

For more customized themes: ggthemes package and ggthemr package
